08:21.308 --> 08:28.178
One from a kind of an argument of the actual text itself, and one is a more kind of

08:28.450 --> 08:30.712
general idea about how God works.

08:31.533 --> 08:34.476
The first point based on the text is this.

08:35.577 --> 08:42.403
The writer of the Hebrews is not writing to generally misbehaving Christians.

08:43.844 --> 08:58.418
I have made a case in some Bible studies previously that there may have been a woman involved, but he, let's say for argument, the writer of Hebrews is writing to a community

08:58.530 --> 09:21.865
of previously Jewish believers who were under persecution at genuine risk of returning back to Judaism because there were greater protections in the Roman laws for Jews than they were for this emerging Christian sect.

09:23.228 --> 09:27.474
So the backstory, the wider context of what is going on,

09:28.034 --> 09:47.533
is that these Jewish believers were considering under persecution, maybe just fully aligning themselves back with Judaism, rather than continuing with their walk with Jesus as their Messiah.

09:47.673 --> 09:49.075
Why does that make a difference?

09:50.456 --> 09:56.722
It makes a difference because in Hebrews 10, as with Hebrews 9,

09:57.666 --> 10:07.761
The writer is comparing the virtues of the new covenant we have walking with Jesus versus the previous Levitical system.

10:08.842 --> 10:16.754
With the previous system, with the Jews, whenever they sinned, they had to go back and make another sacrifice.

10:17.154 --> 10:23.302
You sin, you bring your sacrifice, you sin again, you bring your sacrifice, you sin again, then you have to bring your sacrifice.

10:23.543 --> 10:28.730
You sin, sacrifice sin, sacrifice sin, sacrifice, and you kept doing that.

10:29.311 --> 10:40.386
The writer's point is that if they go back to Judaism, there are no more sacrifices that are going to work to take away your sins.

10:40.606 --> 10:43.570
Now Messiah has come and He's been sacrificed.

10:44.162 --> 10:53.511
The paraphrase is this, and I'm going to share with you the amplified translation of this because it explains this in a more helpful way than maybe I will share with you.

10:54.252 --> 11:00.418
The writer is simply saying, if you continue in sin, where else are you going to go for your sacrifices?

11:00.698 --> 11:07.965
There are no other sacrifices left for you to use because God has brought sacrifice and offering to an end in Jesus.

11:08.265 --> 11:09.407
You reject Him.

11:09.447 --> 11:13.010
You reject God's sacrifice for sins.

11:14.306 --> 11:25.784
So the writer is not saying to that first century community of people, make sure that you don't have a cheeky wink at that person around the corner that's giving you those feels.

11:26.625 --> 11:30.992
Because if you keep on doing that, God's going to say, that's no, that's not the behavior that I accept.

11:31.212 --> 11:31.813
That's too much.

11:31.833 --> 11:32.173
You're off.

11:32.374 --> 11:32.754
You're out.

11:35.418 --> 11:43.090
The context is the writer saying there is one system that you used to live under whereby it was sin

11:43.394 --> 11:49.686
followed by sacrifice, sin followed by sacrifice, but now sacrifices come to an end in Christ.

11:50.167 --> 11:54.174
If you go back to the old system, where you're going to get your forgiveness from?

11:54.234 --> 11:59.384
The only way you can be absolutely forgiven is through Jesus.

11:59.444 --> 12:04.373
You reject Him, then there is no sacrifice for sins left.

12:05.134 --> 12:07.058
The amplified version puts it this way.

12:09.186 --> 12:17.077
If we go unwillfully and deliberately sitting after we receive the knowledge of the truth, there no longer remains a sacrifice to atone for our sins.

12:17.878 --> 12:21.663
That is no further offerings to anticipate.

12:23.045 --> 12:25.188
There's nothing else coming.

12:25.248 --> 12:26.089
You receive that.

12:26.309 --> 12:31.977
Imagine if I said, everybody today who comes to this meeting, you get some food.

12:32.037 --> 12:35.762
And they say, well, I don't like that food.

12:36.290 --> 12:38.292
I say, well, that's the only food you're going to get.

12:38.352 --> 12:41.115
You can come back later, and if it's all eaten, you've got nothing left to eat.

12:41.876 --> 12:46.481
If you reject the means of provision, there is no more provision left.

12:47.042 --> 12:50.265
There's nothing else you can go to to get your provision from.

12:51.166 --> 12:55.671
So this isn't about being too naughty, too often, and God striking you off.

12:56.011 --> 12:59.235
It's saying, choose what system you're going to get your forgiveness from.

12:59.575 --> 13:00.976
You reject Jesus.

13:01.737 --> 13:06.162
There is no other sacrifice for your sins that will work for you.

13:06.274 --> 13:11.239
Okay, another version of this same problem is in Hebrews 6, 4 to 6.

13:13.041 --> 13:28.318
It says this, it is impossible for those who have once been enlightened, who have tasted the heavenly gift, who were shared in the Holy Spirit, who have tasted the goodness of the work of God and the powers of the coming age, who have then fallen away to be brought back to repentance.

13:28.619 --> 13:35.186
To their loss, they are crucifying the Son of God all over again and subjecting Him to a public

13:35.362 --> 13:36.143
disgrace.

13:36.563 --> 13:50.901
Another verse that seems to say that if you were to fall away from Jesus you put yourself in an impossible situation where there is no chance of you continuing to receive the benefits of salvation.

13:51.522 --> 13:52.463
I've heard that preached.

13:52.883 --> 13:56.347
